#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""imap-sync-tests -- the milestone 3b imapsync module's acceptance
suite (src/ams/msclients/imapsync/imap_sync.c), the one-way
IMAP-to-local-store mirror. See revival/doc/claude-history/imap-sync-prompt.md.

Usage:
    revival/tests/imap-sync-tests

Live against the real Fastmail account via the committed netrc_Lookup
and ~/.netrc, exactly as imap-protocol-tests and smtp-protocol-tests do.
Strictly read-only against the mailbox from imapsync's own side: it only
ever issues EXAMINE/UID SEARCH/UID FETCH (FLAGS INTERNALDATE ENVELOPE)/
UID FETCH BODY.PEEK[] -- no STORE/APPEND/CREATE/DELETE/EXPUNGE reaches
the wire from imapsync. Case 3 sends one real message via the committed
SMTP path (smtptest.test) to wdc@fastmail.com only, as the spec
prescribes for the incremental-sync case.

All six cases run against one fresh `mktemp -d` scratch mspath root
(cases 3-6 build on the mirror cases 1-2 already produced) -- the real
`~/.IMAP/fastmail` is never touched, and the real `~/preferences` is
never touched (case 6 uses its own scratch PROFILES file). The scratch
root is removed on exit unless the environment variable
IMAPSYNC_KEEP_SCRATCH is set (useful for inspecting a failure by hand).

Case 1 mirrors the *entire* real INBOX (several thousand messages as of
this writing) and case 5's UIDVALIDITY drill re-mirrors it again from
scratch, so this suite can take a long time (tens of minutes) to run
live.

If ~/.netrc has no usable "machine imap.fastmail.com" stanza, this
suite skips cleanly (like imap-protocol-tests) rather than failing.

Cases W2/W3/W4/W7 (added for the writeback milestone's Gate 2) exercise
imap_sync.c's replay_folder() -- flags replay, purge replay, the
25-purge safety valve, and the stale-UIDVALIDITY skip -- against their
own fresh scratch root and mailbox, entirely separate from cases 1-6's
INBOX mirror above (own tempdir, own imapsync run, no dependency on the
long INBOX pass having completed). ALL destructive traffic in these
cases -- STORE/EXPUNGE/APPEND/CREATE, and every imapsync invocation
that might replay a journal -- is confined to one dedicated mailbox,
WRITE_MAILBOX ("Revival/WritebackTest"), created if absent; INBOX is
never written to anywhere in this suite. This is enforced twice,
independently: imaptest.c's own guard_mailbox() refuses at the C level
for the create/storeflags/expunge/append subcommands regardless of
caller, and this file's own run_imapsync_wb()/imaptest_wb() wrappers
refuse, themselves, to be called with any other mailbox/folder name --
a safety rule this important should not have exactly one enforcement
point. These four cases fabricate well-formed journal lines directly
(following msjournal.c's documented "J1 ..." grammar exactly) rather
than driving a real cui session to produce them: Gate 1's own
imap-writeback-tests suite already proves real capture end-to-end (its
case 1), so these cases test replay_folder() in isolation, faster and
more deterministically -- exactly the same testing strategy the
milestone's own spec calls for in case 4 ("fabricate a journal with 26
purges").
"""

